[3] Pulmonary, pathological findings of COVID-19 ARDS
Date: 18 Feb 2020
Source: The Lancet Respiratory Medicine case report [edited]
https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lanres/article/PIIS2213-2600(20)30076-X/fulltext


Xu Z, Shi L, Wang Y, Zhang J, Huang L, Zhang C, et al. Pathological findings of COVID-19 associated with acute respiratory distress syndrome. Published February 18 2020. The Lancet, Respiratory Medicine. https://doi.org/10.1016/S2213-2600(20)30076-X

Excerpted:
"Biopsy samples were taken from lung, liver, and heart tissue of the patient. Histological examination showed bilateral diffuse alveolar damage with cellular fibromyxoid exudates (figure 2A, B [available at source url]). The right lung showed evident desquamation of pneumocytes and hyaline membrane formation, indicating acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS; figure 2A [available at source url]). The left lung tissue displayed pulmonary oedema with hyaline membrane formation, suggestive of early-phase ARDS (figure 2B [available at source URL]). Interstitial mononuclear inflammatory infiltrates, dominated by lymphocytes, were seen in both lungs. Multinucleated syncytial cells with atypical enlarged pneumocytes characterised by large nuclei, amphophilic granular cytoplasm, and prominent nucleoli were identified in the intra-alveolar spaces, showing viral cytopathic-like changes. No obvious intranuclear or intracytoplasmic viral inclusions were identified.

The pathological features of COVID-19 greatly resemble those seen in SARS and Middle Eastern respiratory syndrome (MERS) coronavirus infection. /4, /5

Although corticosteroid treatment is not routinely recommended to be used for SARS-CoV-2 pneumonia, according to our pathological findings of pulmonary oedema and hyaline membrane formation, timely and appropriate use of corticosteroids together with ventilator support should be considered for the severe patients to prevent ARDS development.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[References are available at source URL. It is not surprising that the pathological findings are similar to those seen with SARS and MERS as the 3 diseases (including COVID-19) are caused by coronavirues, with the SARS and the SARS-CoV-2 being genetically related. - Mod.MPP]

